  "prompt": "What happened in 2008 financial crisis?",
  "response": "The 2008 financial crisis, also known as the Global Financial Crisis (GFC), was a severe worldwide economic crisis considered by many economists to have been the most serious financial crisis since the Great Depression. Here are the key events and factors that contributed to the crisis:\n\n1. **Housing Bubble and Subprime Mortgage Crisis**:\n   - Leading up to the crisis, there was an unprecedented housing bubble in the United States, driven by high demand, speculative investments, and easy access to credit.\n   - Financial institutions provided mortgages to individuals with poor credit histories, known as subprime mortgages. These loans were often made with little regard to the borrowers' ability to repay.\n\n2. **Securitization and Financial Products**:\n   - Banks and financial institutions bundled these subprime mortgages into mortgage-backed securities (MBS) and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs), which were sold to investors.\n   - These complex financial products were rated highly by credit rating agencies, despite their inherent risks.\n\n3. **Failure of Financial Institutions**:\n   - As homeowners began to default on their loans, the value of MBS and CDOs plummeted, leading to massive losses for investors.\n   - Major financial institutions faced liquidity and solvency problems. Lehman Brothers, a large investment bank, filed for bankruptcy in September 2008, marking a significant turning point in the crisis.\n\n4. **Global Impact**:\n   - The crisis quickly spread to global financial markets, causing stock markets to crash and leading to a credit crunch where banks became reluctant to lend money.\n   - Many economies around the world experienced recessions, significant drops in GDP, and high unemployment rates.\n\n5. **Government Interventions**:\n   - Governments and central banks intervened with various measures to stabilize the financial system. In the United States, the Federal Reserve implemented emergency lending programs, and the Treasury Department launched the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP) to purchase toxic assets.\n   - Other countries also implemented stimulus packages and took steps to protect their banking systems.\n\n6. **Regulatory Changes**:\n   - In the aftermath, there was a push for stronger financial regulations to prevent a recurrence. The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to increase oversight and transparency in the financial sector.\n\nThe 2008 financial crisis had long-lasting effects on the global economy, leading to profound changes in financial regulation and a reevaluation of risk management practices in the financial industry.",
